  "prompt": "What would be the quadratic equation for the roots 2+\u221a2 and 2-\u221a2?",
  "response": "To find the quadratic equation whose roots are \\(2 + \\sqrt{2}\\) and \\(2 - \\sqrt{2}\\), we can use Vieta's formulas. According to Vieta's, for a quadratic equation of the form:\n\n\\[\nax^2 + bx + c = 0\n\\]\n\nthe sum of the roots (\\(r_1 + r_2\\)) is equal to \\(-\\frac{b}{a}\\), and the product of the roots (\\(r_1 \\cdot r_2\\)) is equal to \\(\\frac{c}{a}\\).\n\n1. **Calculate the sum of the roots:**\n\n\\[\n(2 + \\sqrt{2}) + (2 - \\sqrt{2}) = 4\n\\]\n\n2. **Calculate the product of the roots:**\n\n\\[\n(2 + \\sqrt{2})(2 - \\sqrt{2}) = 2^2 - (\\sqrt{2})^2 = 4 - 2 = 2\n\\]\n\nNow, knowing the sum and product of the roots, we can set up the quadratic equation using these values. For our case, let \\(a = 1\\) (making the equation monic):\n\n\\[\nx^2 - (\\text{sum of the roots}) x + (\\text{product of the roots}) = 0\n\\]\n\nSubstituting the calculated values:\n\n\\[\nx^2 - 4x + 2 = 0\n\\]\n\nThus, the quadratic equation with roots \\(2 + \\sqrt{2}\\) and \\(2 - \\sqrt{2}\\) is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{x^2 - 4x + 2 = 0}\n\\]",
